00:00:01.159 --> 00:00:09.269
So something I mentioned earlier is that all HTML elements can have attributes.

00:00:09.269 --> 00:00:13.049
Attributes provide additional information about an element and

00:00:13.050 --> 00:00:16.830
are almost always specified in the start tag.

00:00:16.829 --> 00:00:21.794
So what are some examples of what attributes we might want to give elements?

00:00:21.795 --> 00:00:24.420
Well, it varies on the type of element but for

00:00:24.420 --> 00:00:27.000
almost every element an ID would make sense.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.120
An ID is an attribute that will allow us to programmatically

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:34.230
select and manipulate that element based on its ID.

00:00:34.229 --> 00:00:37.454
Another example is source.

00:00:37.454 --> 00:00:42.030
Source comes into handy as an attribute for things like an image tag.

00:00:42.030 --> 00:00:46.820
An image tag will use IMG to say this is going to be an image,

00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:49.310
but to tell it where to pull the image from,

00:00:49.310 --> 00:00:51.350
we use the source attribute.

00:00:51.350 --> 00:00:55.100
Another very useful attribute is href.

00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:59.465
It could be argued that href is really the attributes that the web is built on.

00:00:59.465 --> 00:01:05.855
Because href is what you use to a link to tell it where to go to next.

00:01:05.855 --> 00:01:08.390
So if the web is a set of interconnected links that you

00:01:08.390 --> 00:01:11.349
can follow by pressing on those links,

00:01:11.349 --> 00:01:15.155
the href is what's sending you all around those places.

00:01:15.155 --> 00:01:19.260
So let's take a look at this with some real code.

00:01:19.719 --> 00:01:25.310
So here we are with a file called attributes.html and we're going

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:30.290
to dive into some of the most useful attributes and see what they look like in practice.

00:01:30.290 --> 00:01:34.700
So the first thing I might do is just create a basic div and I'm going to give

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:39.859
it an ID, id equals love.

00:01:39.859 --> 00:01:48.769
We might as well have the text of this say, love will overcome.

00:01:48.769 --> 00:01:51.420
Now, let's first check that it works,

00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:52.875
love will overcome, we see.

00:01:52.875 --> 00:01:55.609
Now, this is jumping ahead a little bit to the CFS lesson,

00:01:55.609 --> 00:02:00.034
but I'm realizing I would really like you to see why an ID might be useful.

00:02:00.034 --> 00:02:03.530
So what I'm going to do here is I'm going to

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:09.485
quickly add some style tags which we'll go over much more in later lessons.

00:02:09.485 --> 00:02:17.240
But now, because I have set the attribute here to the idea of love,

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:20.180
I can access this div in my style.

00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:27.455
We prep end names with a hash sign or a pound mark for IDs.

00:02:27.455 --> 00:02:31.160
So #love is ID love.

00:02:31.159 --> 00:02:36.650
Then, I'm going to say color red.

00:02:36.650 --> 00:02:42.200
Now, we see that the text is red because I've used

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:48.364
the attribute an ID love and then I have used the style rule here to set it to be red.

00:02:48.365 --> 00:02:52.325
That's one example of how setting an attribute can be useful.

00:02:52.324 --> 00:02:54.994
Let's take a look at an image.

00:02:54.995 --> 00:02:57.004
So to make an image,

00:02:57.004 --> 00:03:01.414
I need the image tag and then I need a source.

00:03:01.414 --> 00:03:04.340
I think I have an image here.

